segments.text: I didn't really hear you say testing.
No, but I think it's five minutes.
So I didn't realize that you were the one that got the seed lab out there.
I'll tell you what happened.
Gatesville was being filled with delinquents.
So they were going to build a new school.
Well, the speaker and I at this time was Gus Mutch.
And they were also going to build a school for mentally retarded.
And I said, Gus, I tell you what, you got people in here that you can't control.
And I can, I got, you got people here that you control, and I can.
Let's do this.
Let's get the mentally retarded school the money for that, designated for Brenner, and I'll take the school, the delinquent school.
So
Mr. Healy, who at that time was made, was appropriation.
So it was all set up.
Yeah.
Burnham, buy the land, furnish the land, get him to furnish the land for the school right here.
Uh,
We hit it.
Well, I came down here and talked to, uh, Monroe Honish at that particular time.
Do you remember?
I don't.
Monroe and, uh, and Judge, uh, Semain, and a few other people like that.
Got them together there at the , and told them what I believe I can do.
Of course, they were all happy, because that was going to put a lot of people to work around here.
And there was two, I'm not going to tell you who they were, but there was two people that asked more questions.
All the rest of them put together.
And they didn't give one dime to help buy the land.
Where, as the banks, I think First National furnished about $7,000, $8,000, and Citizen wasn't quite that much.
And then a lot of individuals, like Self and Milton Archer and Murcher and I don't know who, would furnish X number of dollars.
In fact, I feel that's the best of what they furnish.
And we first got enough money together to buy that land.
Well, this neck, if you can recall, this neck came up to the highway, and these colored people on theâ€”well, one of them got the
Sternberger is on the land, and they wanted, I think, at that time, $500 a acre.
I'll be there for you.
At that time, not now.
Anyway, we got the money to buy the whole thing.
And I told the manager, or head man of the delinquent,
We'd get that land there for him if he would give me this neck in there and build us a building.
I'd help him get some extra money in his appropriation.
Mr. Healy had already told me to go ahead and put that proposition to him.
And he'd get the money and put it in there.
So he did.
And so, actually, the, uh, that's what we did.
And they did the, uh, the, uh... Let me call it again.
It was not, uh...
Anyway, before the school was built, there was a fellow by the name of Turman, too.
He's dead now.
And they deeded us that neck up there and built us that building.
And that's the only property that the Texas Department of Agriculture owns.
I didn't know that.
I guess, what did you do in between the time that you became, well, you ended your years as deputy commissioner and then took the job in the Farmers Home Administration?
Were you involved still in agricultural?
I was just on my own.
You said that you were...
You were appointed in August of 1977.
I was the first one in the United States to be appointed.
By Carter?
By Carter.
Or was that, that was just by Carter.
What kind of influence did he have over you when you could do pretty much what you wanted?
I did mostly anything I wanted.
Loaning money.
You have different sections in Temple there.
You had the loan section for cattle, loan section for houses, loan section for community property, community improvement.
Then you had your loan section that would help people to go in business that couldn't afford it, yet they were worthy of it.
And that's what I control.
How long were you in this position?
How many years?
About three and a half, I guess.
Three and a half?
Uh-huh.
I couldn't move early.
I could have stayed on, but this, I don't want this out.
It got to me.
That's when things started tightening up.
And I got there at the end.
People would come in the office that our field people had turned down.
And I was, you might say, the last resort.
And I could see where they couldn't pay for it, no way.
Yet they had taken their land and taken a lot of it.
And it got next to me.
I just couldn't... What I did, I just...
I called the in-house attorney at Scott & White, who I had served in the legislature with, and I told him, I said, now, I know you've got the best doctor up there.
I said, that's the one I want.
I said, I swear to you, Jamie, his name's Jamie Clinton, I believe I've got...
He said, Bill, I'll bet you don't, because I think I know what you're doing.
I'm not the doctor.
And he's an attorney.
And so he went away.
He says, just sit right there.
I'll call you back in about 30 minutes.
I don't know if he did.
He called me back.
He had me an appointment set up with his doctor.
And he set me up with a doctor, a real nice fellow, one of the old ones up there.
He made speeches in Mayo and the University of Mexico.
He was well known in the medical field.
When you go through there, Scott and Mike, they send you around to a specialist in every field.
And they went from the top of my head to my feet.
Because I didn't know what to put on, what to fill out.
Anyway, end of the second day, I went in to see my doctor.
And he...
I said, Bill, you carry your work home with you, don't you?
I said, Doctor, I do.
I worry.
I worry about these poor people.
I said, at one time I had lots and lots of money, but now they've lived it up, and what are they going to do?
They moved out of their places.
You know, anyway, I said, Bill, I...
He said, you shouldn't worry about what you owe them.
You can't do that.
He said, the best thing you can do is go home and take two aspirin and go to bed.
And wound up.
that I have nervous stomach.
Said, Bill, you don't even have an ulcer.
You're nervous.
Your nervous stomach is causing you this trouble.
I still got it.
I just got it back from Staten White last night.
Well, during those years, that was when we had inflation.
Were people really losing their farms because of the economy?
Because they spent too much money.
They kind of lived too high.
That was the cause of most of it.
Then a lot of the products weren't selling like they should.
In 1979, the Overview said that there were like over 14,000 farm programs
under the, in Texas, under the Farmers Home Administration, that was like twice as many as in any other state.
Was this mainly the reason because agriculture was the biggest thing for Texas at that time?
A lot of, you know, we used to have lots of, look here, we used to have, of course you don't remember, but
We used to have lots of cotton here.
At one time, we had about seven or eight gins here in this county.
We don't even have a gin now.
I've noticed it was just peanuts.
That's all.
And they can't make any money out of cattle.
I know, because I raised cattle.
You can't build off of cattle.
Another thing, too, the boys,
and girls were going off to college, just like you, and getting better educated.
And they were not going back to the farm to handle that tractor.
And they were married.
They wanted to take their family out to Austin to eat once in a while.
like people here do.
But you couldn't do it.
You couldn't make that kind of money and pay your taxes and pay for your land.
You cannot, in no way, buy your land, buy your farm equipment and your house and pay for what you raise on the farm at this time.
Do you think agriculture, then, is going down?
What do you predict?
Down, down, down.
I was talking to a man yesterday.
It's Scott and White.
He was from Oklahoma.
He said, well, all of a sudden, we're in such bad shape.
And I was talking to a nurse.
I had some dental work while I was up there.
Not a good dentist here, but since I had the time, I had to sit there and wait for another appointment between the doctors while I went in there.
And she, the nurse, I knew her.
And I said, well, how you doing?
And I told her, we talked.
She said, her home is in Iowa.
She said, she's been up home.
She said, Mr. Pratt, you just don't realize it.

what condition those poor farmers are in and the small business has we there's towns up there with say two and three thousand populations the whole town is boarded up and out do you see um do you see any kind of any field or any area of agriculture that come back do you see any area in agriculture that might
prosper in the next year?
No.
A lot of people at A&M are not really in the agriculture part.
They're in ag business.
That's it.
The ag business people are the only ones making money.
John, David's brother-in-law, he sells out of Kansas City, he sells farm equipment.
But the
A lot of yourâ€”well, the north you go, the worse it gets.
A lot of those people up there are selling out.
Consequently, the ones down this wayâ€”well, Boggy, he bought tractors and things, brought them down here, used them.
He didn't buy anything around here new, because those people up there couldn't sell it.
Do you think the Farmer's Home Administration is working?
Do you think it'll probably phase out because of the economy?
No, it can't phase out.
I say it can't.
Of course, anything can phase out, but no, I don't think it'll phase out because they have mortgaged on too much.
The last year that I was there,
I lent out over $700 million.
How much do you think the state will get back from that?
That's not the state.
That's the federal.
Federal.
Well, they won't get back much in interest, because the interest probably wasn't over 3% or 4% or 5%, something like that.
And they'll get back more from the housing authority that we lent money to build houses.
And they'll get back more from the country water supply.
They'll pay it back.
But the farms will be less and less.
More of them have to be sold.
Another reason of it is when they put the embargo, Carter started that.
He was wrong there.
He was wrong.
Russia.
Because of that Afghanistan mess, you know.
All right.
They put the embargo on them.
We were selling them lots and lots of wheat and corn.
Then they turned around and started buying it from Argentina and other countries and now are buying it cheaper
And consequently, they're not buying from us, not much from us.
That's one reason our farmers are in such bad shape.
So the farmers, they didn't mind selling it to Russia?
Oh, no.
Not as long as we had that dollar.
Mm-hmm.
What area of the Farmers' Home Administration really worked in?
It was not apparently the farming.
Was it housing or...
community, which worked the best, did you think?
Community.
Community.

Um, what... And we, we, uh, are, we lent money to a lot of people that, uh, of course, they were all investigating and wrestling with people that, uh, and they would have to have something to start with and be knowledgeable of the product they were going to make.
And, uh,
We lent them money, and we got most of our money back.
Actually, we didn't loan them any money.
We would guarantee them money, like savings loan up here.
Loan Tina Melcher $50,000 to build a new home.
And she's got a good job.
she'll pay it, and we'll guarantee that she will pay it.
And that's the same thing with most all the other things.
So that's mainly what the state did, just guarantee it?
I'm not a state now.
Well, I mean, the state did for the federal government.
They guaranteed...
The state didn't.
The state didn't have anything to do with the pharmaceutical stuff.
But your job was just to guarantee the federal...
government.
My job was my job was was to use my judgment for this particular people could pay this back.
So what did I know it was a real bad economy time and everything but did Carter
It seemed like he just got into a hole and he didn't know how to get himself out.
But with that, at the end when inflation was really getting bad, were there pressures put on you not to give out loans or anything from the federal government?
There was more put on me to give loans than there was.
They wanted you to give loans?
Some of the senators up there would call me and ask me to loan over the old.
I said, no, I'm not going to sign it.
I don't think you can pay it back.
Oh, I didn't.
I said, well, now, I'll tell you what.
I'll send you the papers up there, and you get them signed up there in Washington.
They said, oh, no, you know we can't do that.
I said, well, I'm not going to sign it.
Period.
So you just took care of Texas, just the state of Texas?
State of Texas.

So since you're an agriculture man, I'll end it by asking you, those years that you were in the Agriculture Department and you had influence in the state were probably the most prosperous years of Texas.
And what do you feel like will be the future
of the Ag Department of Texas and the Farmers Home Administration?
Of course, it depends on the management.
I ran into a man that was being examined, an SCS man, out of A&M.
He's a hot shot.
He's one of the big boys over there.
And we shook hands and talked.
He says, oh, we just had John White back there instead of the man that we got.
He says, that man that we got?
I said, sorry.
Sorry.
Now, of course, I'm not telling you this to be corny or anything like that.
Some of the employees tell me that the Farmers' Home Administration is not loaning as much money
to people that really, they think they can pay back.
Because of, let's just face it, Republicans are a lot more conservative.
And older you get, I'm a lot more conservative now than I was when I was...
your age or even older.
It's just a matter of life.
The older you get, the more conservative you get.
And there it comes.
So do you see yourself as a liberal in your younger days?
Or a conservative liberal?
I never was a real liberal.
I was, I'd say, middle.
because I was raised money-wise conservative.
But the agricultural industry, I think, the future looks like
And a lot of people claim, oh, we ought to get rid of, a lot of you liberals, say we ought to get rid of the corporations.
Oh, no, let these corporations farm.
Well, that's not, I know Tineco, I talked to the director of Tineco, and they control 90% of the almonds
grown in California.
And they sold them.
They wanted the X number of dollars for them.
But two of the main chain stores went in there and said, we'll give you this for them, which was a lot less than this X money.
Your chain stores
control more of it than any of the other corporations that do the farming.
Well, thank you for your interview.
I appreciate it.
Well, that wasn't much.
Good.
Good.
Good.
Good.
Good.
